nsOspf.description: The MIB module to describe the NS-OSPF Version 2 Protocol

Status.name: Status
Status.description: The status of an interface: 'enabled' indicates that it is willing to communicate with other OSPF Routers, while 'disabled' indicates that it is not.

PositiveInteger.name: PositiveInteger
PositiveInteger.description: A positive integer. Values in excess are precluded as unnecessary and prone to interoperability issues.

HelloRange.name: HelloRange
HelloRange.description: The range of intervals on which hello messages are exchanged.

UpToMaxAge.name: UpToMaxAge
UpToMaxAge.description: The values that one might find or configure for variables bounded by the maximum age of an LSA.

DesignatedRouterPriority.name: DesignatedRouterPriority
DesignatedRouterPriority.description: The values defined for the priority of a system for becoming the designated router.

TOSType.name: TOSType
TOSType.description: Type of Service is defined as a mapping to the IP Type of Service Flags as defined in the IP Forwarding Table MIB +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+ | | | | | PRECEDENCE | TYPE OF SERVICE | 0 | | | | | +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+ IP TOS IP TOS Field Policy Field Policy Contents Code Contents Code 0 0 0 0 ==> 0 0 0 0 1 ==> 2 0 0 1 0 ==> 4 0 0 1 1 ==> 6 0 1 0 0 ==> 8 0 1 0 1 ==> 10 0 1 1 0 ==> 12 0 1 1 1 ==> 14 1 0 0 0 ==> 16 1 0 0 1 ==> 18 1 0 1 0 ==> 20 1 0 1 1 ==> 22 1 1 0 0 ==> 24 1 1 0 1 ==> 26 1 1 1 0 ==> 28 1 1 1 1 ==> 30 The remaining values are left for future definition.

nsOspfGeneralTable.name: nsOspfGeneralTable
nsOspfGeneralTable.description: Ospf general information table per VR

nsOspfGeneralEntry.name: nsOspfGeneralEntry
nsOspfGeneralEntry.description: Ospf general information table per VR

nsOspfRouterId.name: nsOspfRouterId
nsOspfRouterId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying the router in the Autonomous System. By convention, to ensure uniqueness, this should default to the value of one of the router's IP interface addresses.

nsOspfAdminStat.name: nsOspfAdminStat
nsOspfAdminStat.description: The administrative status of OSPF in the router. The value 'enabled' denotes that the OSPF Process is active on at least one inter- face; 'disabled' disables it on all inter- faces.

nsOspfVersionNumber.name: nsOspfVersionNumber
nsOspfVersionNumber.description: The deprecated version number of the OSPF proto- col is 2.

nsOspfAreaBdrRtrStatus.name: nsOspfAreaBdrRtrStatus
nsOspfAreaBdrRtrStatus.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 3 Splitting the AS into Areas
nsOspfAreaBdrRtrStatus.description: A flag to note whether this router is an area border router.

nsOspfASBdrRtrStatus.name: nsOspfASBdrRtrStatus
nsOspfASBdrRtrStatus.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 3.3 Classification of routers
nsOspfASBdrRtrStatus.description: A flag to note whether this router is config- ured as an Autonomous System border router.

nsOspfExternLsaCount.name: nsOspfExternLsaCount
nsOspfExternLsaCount.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix A.4.5 AS external link advertisements
nsOspfExternLsaCount.description: The number of external (LS type 5) link-state advertisements in the link-state database.

nsOspfExternLsaCksumSum.name: nsOspfExternLsaCksumSum
nsOspfExternLsaCksumSum.description: The 32-bit unsigned sum of the LS checksums of the external link-state advertisements con- tained in the link-state database. This sum can be used to determine if there has been a change in a router's link state database, and to compare the link-state database of two routers.

nsOspfTOSSupport.name: nsOspfTOSSupport
nsOspfTOSSupport.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix F.1.2 Optional TOS support
nsOspfTOSSupport.description: The router's support for type-of-service rout- ing.

nsOspfOriginateNewLsas.name: nsOspfOriginateNewLsas
nsOspfOriginateNewLsas.description: The number of new link-state advertisements that have been originated. This number is in- cremented each time the router originates a new LSA.

nsOspfRxNewLsas.name: nsOspfRxNewLsas
nsOspfRxNewLsas.description: The number of link-state advertisements re- ceived determined to be new instantiations. This number does not include newer instantia- tions of self-originated link-state advertise- ments.

nsOspfExtLsdbLimit.name: nsOspfExtLsdbLimit
nsOspfExtLsdbLimit.description: The maximum number of non-default AS- external-LSAs entries that can be stored in the link-state database. If the value is -1, then there is no limit. When the number of non-default AS-external-LSAs in a router's link-state database reaches nsOspfExtLsdbLimit, the router enters Overflow- State. The router never holds more than nsOspfExtLsdbLimit non-default AS-external-LSAs in its database. OspfExtLsdbLimit MUST be set identically in all routers attached to the OSPF backbone and/or any regular OSPF area. (i.e., OSPF stub areas and NSSAs are excluded).

nsOspfMulticastExtensions.name: nsOspfMulticastExtensions
nsOspfMulticastExtensions.description: A Bit Mask indicating whether the router is forwarding IP multicast (Class D) datagrams based on the algorithms defined in the Multi- cast Extensions to OSPF. Bit 0, if set, indicates that the router can forward IP multicast datagrams in the router's directly attached areas (called intra-area mul- ticast routing). Bit 1, if set, indicates that the router can forward IP multicast datagrams between OSPF areas (called inter-area multicast routing). Bit 2, if set, indicates that the router can forward IP multicast datagrams between Auto- nomous Systems (called inter-AS multicast rout- ing). Only certain combinations of bit settings are allowed, namely: 0 (no multicast forwarding is enabled), 1 (intra-area multicasting only), 3 (intra-area and inter-area multicasting), 5 (intra-area and inter-AS multicasting) and 7 (multicasting everywhere). By default, no mul- ticast forwarding is enabled.

nsOspfExitOverflowInterval.name: nsOspfExitOverflowInterval
nsOspfExitOverflowInterval.description: The number of seconds that, after entering OverflowState, a router will attempt to leave OverflowState. This allows the router to again originate non-default AS-external-LSAs. When set to 0, the router will not leave Overflow- State until restarted.

nsOspfDemandExtensions.name: nsOspfDemandExtensions
nsOspfDemandExtensions.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix on Demand Routing
nsOspfDemandExtensions.description: The router's support for demand routing.

nsOspfAreaTable.name: nsOspfAreaTable
nsOspfAreaTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 6 The Area Data Struc- ture
nsOspfAreaTable.description: Information describing the configured parame- ters and cumulative statistics of the router's attached areas.

nsOspfAreaEntry.name: nsOspfAreaEntry
nsOspfAreaEntry.description: Information describing the configured parame- ters and cumulative statistics of one of the router's attached areas.

nsOspfAreaId.name: nsOspfAreaId
nsOspfAreaId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfAreaId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying an area. Area ID 0.0.0.0 is used for the OSPF backbone.

nsOspfImportAsExtern.name: nsOspfImportAsExtern
nsOspfImportAsExtern.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfImportAsExtern.description: The area's support for importing AS external link- state advertisements.

nsOspfSpfRuns.name: nsOspfSpfRuns
nsOspfSpfRuns.description: The number of times that the intra-area route table has been calculated using this area's link-state database. This is typically done using Dijkstra's algorithm.

nsOspfAreaBdrRtrCount.name: nsOspfAreaBdrRtrCount
nsOspfAreaBdrRtrCount.description: The total number of area border routers reach- able within this area. This is initially zero, and is calculated in each SPF Pass.

nsOspfAsBdrRtrCount.name: nsOspfAsBdrRtrCount
nsOspfAsBdrRtrCount.description: The total number of Autonomous System border routers reachable within this area. This is initially zero, and is calculated in each SPF Pass.

nsOspfAreaLsaCount.name: nsOspfAreaLsaCount
nsOspfAreaLsaCount.description: The total number of link-state advertisements in this area's link-state database, excluding AS External LSA's.

nsOspfAreaLsaCksumSum.name: nsOspfAreaLsaCksumSum
nsOspfAreaLsaCksumSum.description: The 32-bit unsigned sum of the link-state ad- vertisements' LS checksums contained in this area's link-state database. This sum excludes external (LS type 5) link-state advertisements. The sum can be used to determine if there has been a change in a router's link state data- base, and to compare the link-state database of two routers.

nsOspfAreaSummary.name: nsOspfAreaSummary
nsOspfAreaSummary.description: The variable nsOspfAreaSummary controls the im- port of summary LSAs into stub areas. It has no effect on other areas. If it is noAreaSummary, the router will neither originate nor propagate summary LSAs into the stub area. It will rely entirely on its de- fault route. If it is sendAreaSummary, the router will both summarize and propagate summary LSAs.

nsOspfAreaStatus.name: nsOspfAreaStatus
nsOspfAreaStatus.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative. The internal effect (row removal) is implementation dependent.

nsOspfStubAreaTable.name: nsOspfStubAreaTable
nsOspfStubAreaTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2, Area Parameters
nsOspfStubAreaTable.description: The set of metrics that will be advertised by a default Area Border Router into a stub area.

nsOspfStubAreaEntry.name: nsOspfStubAreaEntry
nsOspfStubAreaEntry.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2, Area Parameters
nsOspfStubAreaEntry.description: The metric for a given Type of Service that will be advertised by a default Area Border Router into a stub area.

nsOspfStubAreaId.name: nsOspfStubAreaId
nsOspfStubAreaId.description: The 32 bit identifier for the Stub Area. On creation, this can be derived from the in- stance.

nsOspfStubTOS.name: nsOspfStubTOS
nsOspfStubTOS.description: The Type of Service associated with the metric. On creation, this can be derived from the instance.

nsOspfStubMetric.name: nsOspfStubMetric
nsOspfStubMetric.description: The metric value applied at the indicated type of service. By default, this equals the least metric at the type of service among the inter- faces to other areas.

nsOspfStubStatus.name: nsOspfStubStatus
nsOspfStubStatus.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative. The internal effect (row removal) is implementation dependent.

nsOspfStubMetricType.name: nsOspfStubMetricType
nsOspfStubMetricType.description: This variable displays the type of metric ad- vertised as a default route.

nsOspfLsdbTable.name: nsOspfLsdbTable
nsOspfLsdbTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12 Link State Adver- tisements
nsOspfLsdbTable.description: The OSPF Process's Link State Database.

nsOspfLsdbAreaId.name: nsOspfLsdbAreaId
nsOspfLsdbAreaId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfLsdbAreaId.description: The 32 bit identifier of the Area from which the LSA was received.

nsOspfLsdbType.name: nsOspfLsdbType
nsOspfLsdbType.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix A.4.1 The Link State Advertisement header
nsOspfLsdbType.description: The type of the link state advertisement. Each link state type has a separate advertise- ment format.

nsOspfLsdbLsid.name: nsOspfLsdbLsid
nsOspfLsdbLsid.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12.1.4 Link State ID
nsOspfLsdbLsid.description: The Link State ID is an LS Type Specific field containing either a Router ID or an IP Address; it identifies the piece of the routing domain that is being described by the advertisement.

nsOspfLsdbRouterId.name: nsOspfLsdbRouterId
nsOspfLsdbRouterId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.1 Global parameters
nsOspfLsdbRouterId.description: The 32 bit number that uniquely identifies the originating router in the Autonomous System.

nsOspfLsdbSequence.name: nsOspfLsdbSequence
nsOspfLsdbSequence.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12.1.6 LS sequence number
nsOspfLsdbSequence.description: The sequence number field is a signed 32-bit integer. It is used to detect old and dupli- cate link state advertisements. The space of sequence numbers is linearly ordered. The larger the sequence number the more recent the advertisement.

nsOspfLsdbAge.name: nsOspfLsdbAge
nsOspfLsdbAge.description: This field is the age of the link state adver- tisement in seconds.

nsOspfLsdbChecksum.name: nsOspfLsdbChecksum
nsOspfLsdbChecksum.description: This field is the checksum of the complete contents of the advertisement, excepting the age field. The age field is excepted so that an advertisement's age can be incremented without updating the checksum. The checksum used is the same that is used for ISO connec- tionless datagrams; it is commonly referred to as the Fletcher checksum.

nsOspfLsdbAdvertisement.name: nsOspfLsdbAdvertisement
nsOspfLsdbAdvertisement.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12 Link State Adver- tisements
nsOspfLsdbAdvertisement.description: The entire Link State Advertisement, including its header.

nsOspfHostTable.name: nsOspfHostTable
nsOspfHostTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.6 Host route param- eters
nsOspfHostTable.description: The list of Hosts, and their metrics, that the router will advertise as host routes.

nsOspfHostEntry.name: nsOspfHostEntry
nsOspfHostEntry.description: A metric to be advertised, for a given type of service, when a given host is reachable.

nsOspfHostIpAddress.name: nsOspfHostIpAddress
nsOspfHostIpAddress.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.6 Host route parame- ters
nsOspfHostIpAddress.description: The IP Address of the Host.

nsOspfHostTOS.name: nsOspfHostTOS
nsOspfHostTOS.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.6 Host route parame- ters
nsOspfHostTOS.description: The Type of Service of the route being config- ured.

nsOspfHostMetric.name: nsOspfHostMetric
nsOspfHostMetric.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.6 Host route parame- ters

nsOspfHostStatus.name: nsOspfHostStatus
nsOspfHostStatus.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative. The internal effect (row removal) is implementation dependent.

nsOspfHostAreaID.name: nsOspfHostAreaID
nsOspfHostAreaID.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfHostAreaID.description: The Area the Host Entry is to be found within. By default, the area that a subsuming OSPF in- terface is in, or 0.0.0.0

nsOspfIfTable.name: nsOspfIfTable
nsOspfIfTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.3 Router interface parameters
nsOspfIfTable.description: The OSPF Interface Table describes the inter- faces from the viewpoint of OSPF.

nsOspfIfEntry.name: nsOspfIfEntry
nsOspfIfEntry.description: The OSPF Interface Entry describes one inter- face from the viewpoint of OSPF.

nsOspfIfIpAddress.name: nsOspfIfIpAddress
nsOspfIfIpAddress.description: The IP address of this OSPF interface.

nsOspfAddressLessIf.name: nsOspfAddressLessIf
nsOspfAddressLessIf.description: For the purpose of easing the instancing of addressed and addressless interfaces; This variable takes the value 0 on interfaces with IP Addresses, and the corresponding value of ifIndex for interfaces having no IP Address.

nsOspfIfAreaId.name: nsOspfIfAreaId
nsOspfIfAreaId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying the area to which the interface connects. Area ID 0.0.0.0 is used for the OSPF backbone.

nsOspfIfType.name: nsOspfIfType
nsOspfIfType.description: The OSPF interface type. By way of a default, this field may be intuited from the corresponding value of ifType. Broad- cast LANs, such as Ethernet and IEEE 802.5, take the value 'broadcast', X.25 and similar technologies take the value 'nbma', and links that are definitively point to point take the value 'pointToPoint'.

nsOspfIfAdminStat.name: nsOspfIfAdminStat
nsOspfIfAdminStat.description: The OSPF interface's administrative status. The value formed on the interface, and the in- terface will be advertised as an internal route to some area. The value 'disabled' denotes that the interface is external to OSPF.

nsOspfIfRtrPriority.name: nsOspfIfRtrPriority
nsOspfIfRtrPriority.description: The priority of this interface. Used in multi-access networks, this field is used in the designated router election algorithm. The value 0 signifies that the router is not eligi- ble to become the designated router on this particular network. In the event of a tie in this value, routers will use their Router ID as a tie breaker.

nsOspfIfTransitDelay.name: nsOspfIfTransitDelay
nsOspfIfTransitDelay.description: The estimated number of seconds it takes to transmit a link state update packet over this interface.

nsOspfIfRetransInterval.name: nsOspfIfRetransInterval
nsOspfIfRetransInterval.description: The number of seconds between link-state ad- vertisement retransmissions, for adjacencies belonging to this interface. This value is also used when retransmitting database descrip- tion and link-state request packets.

nsOspfIfHelloInterval.name: nsOspfIfHelloInterval
nsOspfIfHelloInterval.description: The length of time, in seconds, between the Hello packets that the router sends on the in- terface. This value must be the same for all routers attached to a common network.

nsOspfIfRtrDeadInterval.name: nsOspfIfRtrDeadInterval
nsOspfIfRtrDeadInterval.description: The number of seconds that a router's Hello packets have not been seen before it's neigh- bors declare the router down. This should be some multiple of the Hello interval. This value must be the same for all routers attached to a common network.

nsOspfIfPollInterval.name: nsOspfIfPollInterval
nsOspfIfPollInterval.description: The larger time interval, in seconds, between the Hello packets sent to an inactive non- broadcast multi- access neighbor.

nsOspfIfDesignatedRouter.name: nsOspfIfDesignatedRouter
nsOspfIfDesignatedRouter.description: The IP Address of the Designated Router.

nsOspfIfBackupDesignatedRouter.name: nsOspfIfBackupDesignatedRouter
nsOspfIfBackupDesignatedRouter.description: The IP Address of the Backup Designated Router.

nsOspfIfEvents.name: nsOspfIfEvents
nsOspfIfEvents.description: The number of times this OSPF interface has changed its state, or an error has occurred.

nsOspfIfAuthKey.name: nsOspfIfAuthKey
nsOspfIfAuthKey.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 9 The Interface Data Structure
nsOspfIfAuthKey.description: The Authentication Key. If the Area's Author- ization Type is simplePassword, and the key length is shorter than 8 octets, the agent will left adjust and zero fill to 8 octets. Note that unauthenticated interfaces need no authentication key, and simple password authen- tication cannot use a key of more than 8 oc- tets. Larger keys are useful only with authen- tication mechanisms not specified in this docu- ment. When read, nsOspfIfAuthKey always returns an Oc- tet String of length zero.

nsOspfIfStatus.name: nsOspfIfStatus
nsOspfIfStatus.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative. The internal effect (row removal) is implementation dependent.

nsOspfIfMulticastForwarding.name: nsOspfIfMulticastForwarding
nsOspfIfMulticastForwarding.description: The way multicasts should forwarded on this interface; not forwarded, forwarded as data link multicasts, or forwarded as data link uni- casts. Data link multicasting is not meaning- ful on point to point and NBMA interfaces, and setting nsOspfMulticastForwarding to 0 effective- ly disables all multicast forwarding.

nsOspfIfDemand.name: nsOspfIfDemand
nsOspfIfDemand.description: Indicates whether Demand OSPF procedures (hel- lo supression to FULL neighbors and setting the DoNotAge flag on proogated LSAs) should be per- formed on this interface.

nsOspfIfAuthType.name: nsOspfIfAuthType
nsOspfIfAuthType.description: The authentication type specified for an in- terface. Additional authentication types may be assigned locally.

nsOspfIfMetricTable.name: nsOspfIfMetricTable
nsOspfIfMetricTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.3 Router interface parameters
nsOspfIfMetricTable.description: The TOS metrics for a non-virtual interface identified by the interface index.

nsOspfIfMetricEntry.name: nsOspfIfMetricEntry
nsOspfIfMetricEntry.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.3 Router interface parameters
nsOspfIfMetricEntry.description: A particular TOS metric for a non-virtual in- terface identified by the interface index.

nsOspfIfMetricIpAddress.name: nsOspfIfMetricIpAddress
nsOspfIfMetricIpAddress.description: The IP address of this OSPF interface. On row creation, this can be derived from the in- stance.

nsOspfIfMetricAddressLessIf.name: nsOspfIfMetricAddressLessIf
nsOspfIfMetricAddressLessIf.description: For the purpose of easing the instancing of addressed and addressless interfaces; This variable takes the value 0 on interfaces with IP Addresses, and the value of ifIndex for in- terfaces having no IP Address. On row crea- tion, this can be derived from the instance.

nsOspfIfMetricTOS.name: nsOspfIfMetricTOS
nsOspfIfMetricTOS.description: The type of service metric being referenced. On row creation, this can be derived from the instance.

nsOspfIfMetricValue.name: nsOspfIfMetricValue
nsOspfIfMetricValue.description: The metric of using this type of service on this interface. The default value of the TOS 0 Metric is 10^8 / ifSpeed.

nsOspfIfMetricStatus.name: nsOspfIfMetricStatus
nsOspfIfMetricStatus.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative. The internal effect (row removal) is implementation dependent.

nsOspfVirtIfTable.name: nsOspfVirtIfTable
nsOspfVirtIfTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.4 Virtual link parameters
nsOspfVirtIfTable.description: Information about this router's virtual inter- faces.

nsOspfVirtIfEntry.name: nsOspfVirtIfEntry
nsOspfVirtIfEntry.description: Information about a single Virtual Interface.

nsOspfVirtIfAreaId.name: nsOspfVirtIfAreaId
nsOspfVirtIfAreaId.description: The Transit Area that the Virtual Link traverses. By definition, this is not 0.0.0.0

nsOspfVirtIfNeighbor.name: nsOspfVirtIfNeighbor
nsOspfVirtIfNeighbor.description: The Router ID of the Virtual Neighbor.

nsOspfVirtIfTransitDelay.name: nsOspfVirtIfTransitDelay
nsOspfVirtIfTransitDelay.description: The estimated number of seconds it takes to transmit a link- state update packet over this interface.

nsOspfVirtIfRetransInterval.name: nsOspfVirtIfRetransInterval
nsOspfVirtIfRetransInterval.description: The number of seconds between link-state ad- vertisement retransmissions, for adjacencies belonging to this interface. This value is also used when retransmitting database descrip- tion and link-state request packets. This value should be well over the expected round- trip time.

nsOspfVirtIfHelloInterval.name: nsOspfVirtIfHelloInterval
nsOspfVirtIfHelloInterval.description: The length of time, in seconds, between the Hello packets that the router sends on the in- terface. This value must be the same for the virtual neighbor.

nsOspfVirtIfRtrDeadInterval.name: nsOspfVirtIfRtrDeadInterval
nsOspfVirtIfRtrDeadInterval.description: The number of seconds that a router's Hello packets have not been seen before it's neigh- bors declare the router down. This should be some multiple of the Hello interval. This value must be the same for the virtual neigh- bor.

nsOspfVirtIfEvents.name: nsOspfVirtIfEvents
nsOspfVirtIfEvents.description: The number of state changes or error events on this Virtual Link

nsOspfVirtIfAuthKey.name: nsOspfVirtIfAuthKey
nsOspfVirtIfAuthKey.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 9 The Interface Data Structure
nsOspfVirtIfAuthKey.description: If Authentication Type is simplePassword, the device will left adjust and zero fill to 8 oc- tets. Note that unauthenticated interfaces need no authentication key, and simple password authen- tication cannot use a key of more than 8 oc- tets. Larger keys are useful only with authen- tication mechanisms not specified in this docu- ment. When read, nsOspfVifAuthKey always returns a string of length zero.

nsOspfVirtIfStatus.name: nsOspfVirtIfStatus
nsOspfVirtIfStatus.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative. The internal effect (row removal) is implementation dependent.

nsOspfVirtIfAuthType.name: nsOspfVirtIfAuthType
nsOspfVirtIfAuthType.description: The authentication type specified for a virtu- al interface. Additional authentication types may be assigned locally.

nsOspfNbrTable.name: nsOspfNbrTable
nsOspfNbrTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 10 The Neighbor Data Structure
nsOspfNbrTable.description: A table of non-virtual neighbor information.

nsOspfNbrEntry.name: nsOspfNbrEntry
nsOspfNbrEntry.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 10 The Neighbor Data Structure
nsOspfNbrEntry.description: The information regarding a single neighbor.

nsOspfNbrIpAddr.name: nsOspfNbrIpAddr
nsOspfNbrIpAddr.description: The IP address this neighbor is using in its IP Source Address. Note that, on addressless links, this will not be 0.0.0.0, but the ad- dress of another of the neighbor's interfaces.

nsOspfNbrAddressLessIndex.name: nsOspfNbrAddressLessIndex
nsOspfNbrAddressLessIndex.description: On an interface having an IP Address, zero. On addressless interfaces, the corresponding value of ifIndex in the Internet Standard MIB. On row creation, this can be derived from the instance.

nsOspfNbrRtrId.name: nsOspfNbrRtrId
nsOspfNbrRtrId.description: A 32-bit integer (represented as a type IpAd- dress) uniquely identifying the neighboring router in the Autonomous System.

nsOspfNbrOptions.name: nsOspfNbrOptions
nsOspfNbrOptions.description: A Bit Mask corresponding to the neighbor's op- tions field. Bit 0, if set, indicates that the system will operate on Type of Service metrics other than TOS 0. If zero, the neighbor will ignore all metrics except the TOS 0 metric. Bit 1, if set, indicates that the associated area accepts and operates on external informa- tion; if zero, it is a stub area. Bit 2, if set, indicates that the system is ca- pable of routing IP Multicast datagrams; i.e., that it implements the Multicast Extensions to OSPF. Bit 3, if set, indicates that the associated area is an NSSA. These areas are capable of carrying type 7 external advertisements, which are translated into type 5 external advertise- ments at NSSA borders.

nsOspfNbrPriority.name: nsOspfNbrPriority
nsOspfNbrPriority.description: The priority of this neighbor in the designat- ed router election algorithm. The value 0 sig- nifies that the neighbor is not eligible to be- come the designated router on this particular network.

nsOspfNbrState.name: nsOspfNbrState
nsOspfNbrState.description: The State of the relationship with this Neigh- bor.

nsOspfNbrEvents.name: nsOspfNbrEvents
nsOspfNbrEvents.description: The number of times this neighbor relationship has changed state, or an error has occurred.

nsOspfNbrLsRetransQLen.name: nsOspfNbrLsRetransQLen
nsOspfNbrLsRetransQLen.description: The deprecated length of the retransmission queue.

nsOspfNbmaNbrStatus.name: nsOspfNbmaNbrStatus
nsOspfNbmaNbrStatus.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative. The internal effect (row removal) is implementation dependent.

nsOspfNbmaNbrPermanence.name: nsOspfNbmaNbrPermanence
nsOspfNbmaNbrPermanence.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. 'dynamic' and 'permanent' refer to how the neighbor became known.

nsOspfNbrHelloSuppressed.name: nsOspfNbrHelloSuppressed
nsOspfNbrHelloSuppressed.description: Indicates whether Hellos are being suppressed to the neighbor

nsOspfVirtNbrTable.name: nsOspfVirtNbrTable
nsOspfVirtNbrTable.description: A table of virtual neighbor information.

nsOspfVirtNbrRtrId.name: nsOspfVirtNbrRtrId
nsOspfVirtNbrRtrId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying the neighboring router in the Autonomous System.

nsOspfVirtNbrIpAddr.name: nsOspfVirtNbrIpAddr
nsOspfVirtNbrIpAddr.description: The IP address this Virtual Neighbor is us- ing.

nsOspfVirtNbrOptions.name: nsOspfVirtNbrOptions
nsOspfVirtNbrOptions.description: A Bit Mask corresponding to the neighbor's op- tions field. Bit 1, if set, indicates that the system will operate on Type of Service metrics other than TOS 0. If zero, the neighbor will ignore all metrics except the TOS 0 metric. Bit 2, if set, indicates that the system is Network Multicast capable; ie, that it imple- ments OSPF Multicast Routing.

nsOspfVirtNbrState.name: nsOspfVirtNbrState
nsOspfVirtNbrState.description: The state of the Virtual Neighbor Relation- ship.

nsOspfVirtNbrEvents.name: nsOspfVirtNbrEvents
nsOspfVirtNbrEvents.description: The number of times this virtual link has changed its state, or an error has occurred.

nsOspfVirtNbrLsRetransQLen.name: nsOspfVirtNbrLsRetransQLen
nsOspfVirtNbrLsRetransQLen.description: The deprecated length of the retransmission queue.

nsOspfVirtNbrHelloSuppressed.name: nsOspfVirtNbrHelloSuppressed
nsOspfVirtNbrHelloSuppressed.description: Indicates whether Hellos are being suppressed to the neighbor

nsOspfExtLsdbTable.name: nsOspfExtLsdbTable
nsOspfExtLsdbTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12 Link State Adver- tisements
nsOspfExtLsdbTable.description: The OSPF Process's Links State Database.

nsOspfExtLsdbType.name: nsOspfExtLsdbType
nsOspfExtLsdbType.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix A.4.1 The Link State Advertisement header
nsOspfExtLsdbType.description: The type of the link state advertisement. Each link state type has a separate advertise- ment format.

nsOspfExtLsdbLsid.name: nsOspfExtLsdbLsid
nsOspfExtLsdbLsid.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12.1.4 Link State ID
nsOspfExtLsdbLsid.description: The Link State ID is an LS Type Specific field containing either a Router ID or an IP Address; it identifies the piece of the routing domain that is being described by the advertisement.

nsOspfExtLsdbRouterId.name: nsOspfExtLsdbRouterId
nsOspfExtLsdbRouterId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.1 Global parameters
nsOspfExtLsdbRouterId.description: The 32 bit number that uniquely identifies the originating router in the Autonomous System.

nsOspfExtLsdbSequence.name: nsOspfExtLsdbSequence
nsOspfExtLsdbSequence.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12.1.6 LS sequence number
nsOspfExtLsdbSequence.description: The sequence number field is a signed 32-bit integer. It is used to detect old and dupli- cate link state advertisements. The space of sequence numbers is linearly ordered. The larger the sequence number the more recent the advertisement.

nsOspfExtLsdbAge.name: nsOspfExtLsdbAge
nsOspfExtLsdbAge.description: This field is the age of the link state adver- tisement in seconds.

nsOspfExtLsdbChecksum.name: nsOspfExtLsdbChecksum
nsOspfExtLsdbChecksum.description: This field is the checksum of the complete contents of the advertisement, excepting the age field. The age field is excepted so that an advertisement's age can be incremented without updating the checksum. The checksum used is the same that is used for ISO connec- tionless datagrams; it is commonly referred to as the Fletcher checksum.

nsOspfExtLsdbAdvertisement.name: nsOspfExtLsdbAdvertisement
nsOspfExtLsdbAdvertisement.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12 Link State Adver- tisements
nsOspfExtLsdbAdvertisement.description: The entire Link State Advertisement, including its header.

nsOspfAreaAggregateTable.name: nsOspfAreaAggregateTable
nsOspfAreaAggregateTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfAreaAggregateTable.description: A range of IP addresses specified by an IP address/IP network mask pair. For example, class B address range of X.X.X.X with a network mask of 255.255.0.0 includes all IP addresses from X.X.0.0 to X.X.255.255. Note that if ranges are configured such that one range sub- sumes another range (e.g., 10.0.0.0 mask 255.0.0.0 and 10.1.0.0 mask 255.255.0.0), the most specific match is the preferred one.

nsOspfAreaAggregateEntry.name: nsOspfAreaAggregateEntry
nsOspfAreaAggregateEntry.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfAreaAggregateEntry.description: A range of IP addresses specified by an IP address/IP network mask pair. For example, class B address range of X.X.X.X with a network mask of 255.255.0.0 includes all IP addresses from X.X.0.0 to X.X.255.255. Note that if ranges are range configured such that one range subsumes another range (e.g., 10.0.0.0 mask 255.0.0.0 and 10.1.0.0 mask 255.255.0.0), the most specific match is the preferred one.

nsOspfAreaAggregateAreaID.name: nsOspfAreaAggregateAreaID
nsOspfAreaAggregateAreaID.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfAreaAggregateAreaID.description: The Area the Address Aggregate is to be found within.

nsOspfAreaAggregateLsdbType.name: nsOspfAreaAggregateLsdbType
nsOspfAreaAggregateLsdbType.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix A.4.1 The Link State Advertisement header
nsOspfAreaAggregateLsdbType.description: The type of the Address Aggregate. This field specifies the Lsdb type that this Address Ag- gregate applies to.

nsOspfAreaAggregateNet.name: nsOspfAreaAggregateNet
nsOspfAreaAggregateNet.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfAreaAggregateNet.description: The IP Address of the Net or Subnet indicated by the range.

nsOspfAreaAggregateMask.name: nsOspfAreaAggregateMask
nsOspfAreaAggregateMask.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
nsOspfAreaAggregateMask.description: The Subnet Mask that pertains to the Net or Subnet.

nsOspfAreaAggregateStatus.name: nsOspfAreaAggregateStatus
nsOspfAreaAggregateStatus.description: This variable displays the status of the en- try. Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative. The internal effect (row removal) is implementation dependent.

nsOspfAreaAggregateEffect.name: nsOspfAreaAggregateEffect
nsOspfAreaAggregateEffect.description: Subnets subsumed by ranges either trigger the advertisement of the indicated aggregate (ad- vertiseMatching), or result in the subnet's not being advertised at all outside the area.
